{"id":"0811.0615","submitter":"Simone Callegari","authors":"Simone Callegari (Univ. Zurich), Lucio Mayer (Univ. & ETH Zurich),\n  Stelios Kazantzidis (OSU/CCAPP), Monica Colpi (Univ. Milano-Bicocca), Fabio\n  Governato (Univ. Washington), Thomas Quinn (Univ. Washington) and James\n  Wadsley (McMaster Univ.)","title":"Pairing of Supermassive Black Holes in unequal-mass galaxy mergers","comments":"Accepted for publication in ApJL, 5 pages, 2 figures","journal-ref":"Astrophys.J.696:L89-L92,2009","doi":"10.1088/0004-637X/696/1/L89","report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We examine the pairing process of supermassive black holes (SMBHs) down to\nscales of 20-100 pc using a set of N-body/SPH simulations of binary mergers of\ndisk galaxies with mass ratios of 1:4 and 1:10. Our numerical experiments are\ndesigned to represent merger events occurring at various cosmic epochs. The\ninitial conditions of the encounters are consistent with the LambdaCDM paradigm\nof structure formation, and the simulations include the effects of radiative\ncooling, star formation, and supernovae feedback. We find that the pairing of\nSMBHs depends sensitively on the amount of baryonic mass preserved in the\ncenter of the companion galaxies during the last phases of the merger. In\nparticular, due to the combination of gasdynamics and star formation, we find\nthat a pair of SMBHs can form in 1:10 minor mergers provided that galaxies are\nrelatively gas-rich (gas fractions of 30% of the disk mass) and that the\nmergers occur at relatively high redshift (z~3), when dynamical friction\ntimescales are shorter. Since 1:10 mergers are most common events during the\nassembly of galaxies, and mergers are more frequent at high redshift when\ngalaxies are also more gas-rich, our results have positive implications for\nfuture gravitational wave experiments such as the Laser Interferometer Space\nAntenna.\n","versions":[{"versio