{"id":"0811.0810","submitter":"Antony Valentini","authors":"Antony Valentini","title":"De Broglie-Bohm Pilot-Wave Theory: Many Worlds in Denial?","comments":"31 pages, 2 figures. To appear in: 'Everett and his Critics', eds. S.\n  W. Saunders et al. (Oxford University Press, 2009)","journal-ref":"'Many Worlds? Everett, Quantum Theory, and Reality', eds. S.\n  Saunders et al. (Oxford University Press, 2010), pp. 476--509","doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph gr-qc hep-th","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We reply to claims (by Deutsch, Zeh, Brown and Wallace) that the pilot-wave\ntheory of de Broglie and Bohm is really a many-worlds theory with a superfluous\nconfiguration appended to one of the worlds. Assuming that pilot-wave theory\ndoes contain an ontological pilot wave (a complex-valued field in configuration\nspace), we show that such claims arise from not interpreting pilot-wave theory\non its own terms. Specifically, the theory has its own ('subquantum') theory of\nmeasurement, and in general describes a 'nonequilibrium' state that violates\nthe Born rule. Furthermore, in realistic models of the classical limit, one\ndoes not obtain localised pieces of an ontological pilot wave following\nalternative macroscopic trajectories: from a de Broglie-Bohm viewpoint,\nalternative trajectories are merely mathematical and not ontological. Thus,\nfrom the perspective of pilot-wave theory itself, many worlds are an illusion.\nIt is further argued that, even leaving pilot-wave theory aside, the theory of\nmany worlds is rooted in the intrinsically unlikely assumption that quantum\nmeasurements should be modelled on classical measurements, and is therefore\nunlikely to be true.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 5 Nov 2008 20:34:46 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 5 Nov 2008 21:55:12 GMT"}],"update_date":"2011-01-27"}
